Now I understand the problem clearly. In `result.go`, line 271-276:

```go
if len(query.Columns) == 1 && query.Columns[0].EmbedTable == nil {
    c := query.Columns[0]
    name := columnName(c, 0)
    name = strings.Replace(name, "$", "_", -1)
    gq.Ret = QueryValue{
        Name:      escape(name),
        ...
    }
}
```

The return value `Name` is set to the column name. When the column name matches the parameter name (e.g., both are `email`), the `Var` declaration is skipped because `Arg.Pair` == `Ret.Pair` and `Arg.DefineType` == `Ret.DefineType`.

The fix should ensure that when the arg name and ret name are the same, the Go code still creates a separate variable for the return value. Let me look at the template more carefully to figure out the best fix.

Looking at the template again:
```
{{- if or (ne .Arg.Pair .Ret.Pair) (ne .Arg.DefineType .Ret.DefineType) }}
var {{.Ret.Name}} {{.Ret.Type}}
{{- end}}
```

The issue is that when `.Arg.Pair` equals `.Ret.Pair` (both are `email string`) and `.Arg.DefineType` equals `.Ret.DefineType` (both are `string`), no declaration is emitted, and `row.Scan(&email)` scans into the argument `email`, which on error returns the input value.

