Now let me understand how the template condition works. Let me look at the template logic more carefully:

```
{{- if or (ne .Arg.Pair .Ret.Pair) (ne .Arg.DefineType .Ret.DefineType) }}
var {{.Ret.Name}} {{.Ret.Type}}
{{- end}}
```

This means: "if the arg pair differs from the ret pair OR the arg type differs from the ret type, declare a var."

When arg is `email string` and ret is `email string`, both `Pair` and `DefineType` are the same, so no var is declared, and row.Scan writes into the argument `email`.

The best fix is to change the template condition to also check if the arg name equals the ret name. If they share the same name, we should always declare a separate var. Alternatively, we could modify `result.go` to give the return variable a different name when it collides with the argument.

Let me look at how this is handled in the pgx template too:

